WEBVTT

00:03.568 --> 00:03.786
.

00:03.829 --> 00:06.093
- Is that normal?

00:06.136 --> 00:08.182
[intense music]

00:08.225 --> 00:11.185
Okay, what does that mean?
- What does what mean?

00:11.228 --> 00:12.664
[sighs]

00:12.708 --> 00:15.102
- You're sure, Doctor?

00:15.145 --> 00:16.451
♪

00:16.494 --> 00:18.018
Okay.

00:18.061 --> 00:19.410
♪

00:19.454 --> 00:21.412
Thank you, Suzanne.
- What did she say?

00:21.456 --> 00:24.502
- A lot of things.

00:24.546 --> 00:27.157
- Okay, like...?

00:27.201 --> 00:29.246
- The placenta previa resolved.

00:29.290 --> 00:32.206
- It resolved?
- It corrected itself.

00:32.249 --> 00:33.555
- It corrected itself?

00:33.598 --> 00:35.383
- I can have
a natural childbirth.

00:35.426 --> 00:36.688
You don't have
to repeat that part.

00:36.732 --> 00:38.647
- This is amazing.
- [laughing]

00:38.690 --> 00:40.257
- Oh, my goodness, the baby.

00:40.301 --> 00:41.737
Sorry, I just--we're gonna have
a birth right now.

00:41.780 --> 00:43.347
- There's more.
- There's more?

00:43.391 --> 00:46.176
- I am no longer chained
to that hateful bed.

00:46.220 --> 00:48.352
- Hate that bed.
I think we should celebrate.

00:48.396 --> 00:50.180
I think we should rent a boat
on the Hudson.

00:50.224 --> 00:52.052
I think we should go skiing
in the Alps.

00:52.095 --> 00:54.489
I think we should just hike
a mountain.

00:54.532 --> 00:56.491
- Or we could just go
for dinner.

00:56.534 --> 00:58.449
- Yeah.

00:58.493 --> 01:01.061
Well, then would you maybe...

01:01.104 --> 01:03.106
join me for dinner tonight?

01:03.150 --> 01:05.587
- Are you asking me on a date,
Max Goodwin?

01:05.630 --> 01:09.069
- Yes, I am, Georgia Goodwin.

01:09.112 --> 01:11.201
No, um...

01:11.245 --> 01:12.724
[chuckles]
Crap, I can't.

01:12.768 --> 01:16.250
I have the fund-raiser
for the hospital.

01:16.293 --> 01:17.381
- Ouch.

01:17.425 --> 01:19.427
Your favorite.
- Hmm.

01:19.470 --> 01:22.299
This weekend?

01:22.343 --> 01:23.518
Maybe?

01:23.561 --> 01:25.389
- This weekend.

01:25.433 --> 01:27.696
Definitely.

01:27.739 --> 01:30.699
[upbeat music]

01:30.742 --> 01:35.312
♪

01:35.356 --> 01:38.359
- You're in a good mood.
- It's a good news kind of day.

01:38.402 --> 01:39.664
- [laughs]
Let me guess--

01:39.708 --> 01:41.405
getting ready for tonight's
schmooze-fest.

01:41.449 --> 01:43.320
- Georgia's off bed rest.
The baby is healthy.

01:43.364 --> 01:45.453
We are gonna start
dating again.

01:45.496 --> 01:46.889
- [laughs]

01:46.932 --> 01:48.760
- I know the order of that's
a little weird,

01:48.804 --> 01:50.414
but, uh, I'm excited.

01:50.458 --> 01:52.590
- You--you still haven't
told her.

01:52.634 --> 01:54.810
- [scoffs]
You know, it just--

01:54.853 --> 01:57.552
it wasn't the right moment.

01:57.595 --> 01:59.423
- There's never
a right moment

01:59.467 --> 02:01.121
to tell someone
you have cancer.

02:01.164 --> 02:02.774
Just tell them.

02:02.818 --> 02:06.126
- Can't she just have one day
without worrying about someone?

02:06.169 --> 02:07.649
About me, about the baby?

02:07.692 --> 02:10.173
Just one day.

02:10.217 --> 02:12.132
- You swore
that you would tell her

02:12.175 --> 02:13.829
once she was out
of the woods.

02:13.872 --> 02:16.658
She's out.

02:16.701 --> 02:18.486
- I can't tell her today.

02:18.529 --> 02:19.922
You know why?

02:19.965 --> 02:21.924
- 'Cause it's "a good news
kind of day."

02:21.967 --> 02:24.187
- Took the words right out
of my mouth.

02:24.231 --> 02:26.450
- Yeah, my parents--
they're not even coming

02:26.494 --> 02:28.235
to see me or the kids.

02:28.278 --> 02:30.150
They just happen to be in town
for their annual binge

02:30.193 --> 02:32.630
of Broadway musicals that
I will never be able to afford.

02:32.674 --> 02:34.937
Waitress, right orchestra.

02:34.980 --> 02:37.548
- But you invited them
for the fund-raiser.

02:37.592 --> 02:39.420
- I did, yeah.

02:39.463 --> 02:41.726
Yeah, I mean, my--
my oldest, Sameera, has no idea

02:41.770 --> 02:44.164
there's any tension--
as it should be--

02:44.207 --> 02:46.688
and she just, like,
loves my parents, you know?

02:46.731 --> 02:48.559
And I guess...

02:48.603 --> 02:50.648
I want them to love her, too,
and her brothers.

02:50.692 --> 02:52.476
You know, when we first
brought them back

02:52.520 --> 02:55.175
from Bangladesh,
they just happened

02:55.218 --> 02:57.220
to be in town again
for "Hamilton"--

02:57.264 --> 02:58.308
center orchestra.

02:58.352 --> 02:59.657
Thank you very much, Pop.

02:59.701 --> 03:01.659
But I've gotten over that.
- Clearly.

03:01.703 --> 03:03.487
- You know, then we rode
the paddleboats

03:03.531 --> 03:05.663
in Central Park.
- The ones shaped like swans?

03:05.707 --> 03:07.361
- Yeah, exactly those ones.

03:07.404 --> 03:09.711
And now Sameera
is obsessed with swans.

03:09.754 --> 03:11.234
She even learned how to make

03:11.278 --> 03:13.193
those little swan napkins
for them.

03:13.236 --> 03:15.195
Hey, uh, she can make you one
tonight, if you ask her.

03:15.238 --> 03:16.674
- Oh.

03:16.718 --> 03:19.677
Uh, not this year, my friend.
- Really? Why?

03:19.721 --> 03:22.941
Last year you said
you wished you'd gone.

03:22.985 --> 03:25.379
- I'm not ready.

03:25.422 --> 03:27.598
- Okay, I understand.

03:27.642 --> 03:29.470
In that case, you should
really consider giving

03:29.513 --> 03:31.341
those tickets to somebody,
'cause some of your residents

03:31.385 --> 03:34.344
would just kill
to be at that thing.

03:34.388 --> 03:36.259
- That's not a bad idea.
- I know, thank you.

03:36.303 --> 03:37.869
Okay, that's it.

03:37.913 --> 03:40.524
I'll send you my bill.

03:42.483 --> 03:45.442
- Whoa, whoa, Nelly!

03:45.486 --> 03:47.444
I mean, uh, I prefer coffee.

03:47.488 --> 03:49.272
- It's hMG.

03:49.316 --> 03:50.752
- Wow.

03:50.795 --> 03:52.841
So you're, uh--
- Trying, yes.

03:52.884 --> 03:54.712
- Have you already picked out
a donor?

03:54.756 --> 03:56.540
Follow-up question--
is he ripped?

03:56.584 --> 03:58.890
- [laughs]
Hardly.

03:58.934 --> 04:00.805
I'm just trying to trick
my stupid body

04:00.849 --> 04:03.895
into producing eggs.

04:03.939 --> 04:06.724
- Well...

04:06.768 --> 04:08.726
I'm really proud of you,

04:08.770 --> 04:10.380
you know...

04:10.424 --> 04:11.903
for trying.

04:11.947 --> 04:15.777
- Can you believe
that I'm considered geriatric?

04:15.820 --> 04:18.693
- You want a hand with that?

04:18.736 --> 04:20.738
I mean, 'cause you're
so old and all.

04:20.782 --> 04:23.393
- [chuckles]

04:23.437 --> 04:27.310
Thank you.

04:27.354 --> 04:28.311
[grunts]

04:28.355 --> 04:30.748
[both chuckle]

04:33.316 --> 04:35.971
- Oh, bonjour
from Pan de Vie.

04:36.014 --> 04:39.409
You can just, um, swipe.

04:39.453 --> 04:41.977
Bonjourfrom Pain de Vie.

04:42.020 --> 04:43.413
- "Bonjour"?

04:43.457 --> 04:45.459
- It's a new thing
they're making us say.

04:45.502 --> 04:46.938
It's so dorky.
[chuckles]

04:46.982 --> 04:49.376
Uh, you want your usual?
- Yeah.

04:49.419 --> 04:50.942
- Okay.

04:52.509 --> 04:54.381
- Ella.
- Oui?

04:54.424 --> 04:55.730
- The hospital fund-raiser
is this evening,

04:55.773 --> 04:58.428
and I have two tickets.

04:58.472 --> 04:59.951
- Oh, wow, uh--

04:59.995 --> 05:02.954
- I thought if you wished
to go...

05:02.998 --> 05:04.956
- Yeah, uh, that would be
really nice.

05:05.000 --> 05:08.656
Thank you.
- No, no.

05:08.699 --> 05:12.442
- I'll meet you in the lobby
when I get off.

05:12.486 --> 05:13.965
Bonjourfrom Pain de Vie.

05:14.009 --> 05:16.881
- [stammering]
- Two tall cappuccinos.

05:16.925 --> 05:18.709
- You can swipe.

05:20.624 --> 05:21.930
- I can't believe
you're actually going

05:21.973 --> 05:23.366
to this thing tonight.

05:23.410 --> 05:24.759
All it's gonna be
is stuffy donors

05:24.802 --> 05:26.543
acting stuffy and boring.

05:26.587 --> 05:28.850
- Did I mention the full bar?
- Oh, I'm so jealous.

05:28.893 --> 05:30.634
- I don't think you fully grasp
what just happened.

05:30.678 --> 05:32.462
- What'd you bring us?
- Car crash.

05:32.506 --> 05:33.811
Dan Marken, 66-year-old male.

05:33.855 --> 05:35.552
Stable vitals with
an arm laceration.

05:35.596 --> 05:37.467
- Christopher Marken, VSS.

05:37.511 --> 05:39.687
42 years old with
single-leg crush injury.

05:39.730 --> 05:42.124
- Okay, put them
in bays 29 and 30.

05:42.167 --> 05:43.778
- I was trying
to save our lives.

05:43.821 --> 05:45.649
Car made a crazy left.
- You made a crazy right.

05:45.693 --> 05:47.477
- There's no such thing
as a crazy right.

05:47.521 --> 05:49.131
You're not crossing
traffic lines.

05:49.174 --> 05:51.829
It's not my fault no one uses
their blinkers anymore.

05:51.873 --> 05:53.483
- No, it's your fault--
- Looks like you're gonna have

05:53.527 --> 05:55.485
as much fun as I am tonight.
- I hate you.

05:55.529 --> 05:58.009
[pager beeping]

05:58.053 --> 06:00.577
- [sighs]
Damn it.

06:03.406 --> 06:04.755
- Slow down.

06:04.799 --> 06:06.148
[alarm blaring]
- I'm on the Code Team.

06:06.191 --> 06:07.845
- Rules are rules.
Empty your pockets.

06:07.889 --> 06:12.763
Phones, pagers...
- Someone is dying in there.

06:12.807 --> 06:15.375
- He's over here.

06:15.418 --> 06:17.420
- Guy just dropped
like a sack of potatoes.

06:17.464 --> 06:18.726
- Status, Hedera?
- Manny Harris.

06:18.769 --> 06:20.380
Shallow to no breathing.
No pulse.

06:20.423 --> 06:22.120
Chest compression
for three minutes.

06:22.164 --> 06:23.861
- Paddles.
[paddles whirring]

06:23.905 --> 06:25.776
Charge to 200.

06:25.820 --> 06:26.995
Clear.

06:27.038 --> 06:30.172
[flatline]

06:30.215 --> 06:34.568
Going again.
[paddles whirring]

06:34.611 --> 06:36.570
Clear.

06:36.613 --> 06:38.702
[monitor beeping]

06:38.746 --> 06:40.400
He's back.

06:40.443 --> 06:42.053
It's faint, but he's back.

06:42.097 --> 06:45.056
[beeping continues]

06:45.100 --> 06:48.059
[dramatic music]

06:48.103 --> 06:49.844
♪

06:49.887 --> 06:52.063
Did he complain about anything
before he collapsed?

06:52.107 --> 06:54.152
- No.

06:54.196 --> 06:56.416
Hey, Jeffers, did he say
anything to you?

06:56.459 --> 06:58.548
- No, nothing.

06:58.592 --> 07:03.118
♪

07:05.990 --> 07:08.645
- Across, under,
and through.

07:08.689 --> 07:11.561
- Always been more of a scrubs
and sneakers kind of guy.

07:11.605 --> 07:14.477
- Well, listen, Max, I need
to talk to you about tonight.

07:14.521 --> 07:16.566
- I think I have all
the salient details.

07:16.610 --> 07:20.091
Schmooze donors, get money, uh,
hospital keeps running.

07:20.135 --> 07:22.616
- So this whole evening
is about you.

07:22.659 --> 07:24.922
You're the face
of this hospital now,

07:24.966 --> 07:26.837
and the donors are gonna
look to you

07:26.881 --> 07:30.014
to see that you have plans
for fiscal responsibility.

07:30.058 --> 07:32.582
So you need to assure them

07:32.626 --> 07:34.628
that this hospital
is a good investment.

07:34.671 --> 07:36.630
- Fiscal thing is really not
my strong suit.

07:36.673 --> 07:39.197
I prefer to talk
about the patients.

07:39.241 --> 07:40.938
- And does that work?

07:40.982 --> 07:42.810
- Not really, no.

07:42.853 --> 07:47.031
- How in God's name did you
ever raise money in Chinatown?

07:47.075 --> 07:49.251
- I had a secret weapon.

07:49.294 --> 07:51.209
- Really?

07:51.253 --> 07:53.734
Well, dust it off, kid, because
you're gonna need it tonight.

07:53.777 --> 07:56.127
- [chuckles]
I'll do my best.

07:56.171 --> 07:57.912
- Let me put this to you

07:57.955 --> 08:00.480
a different way, Max.

08:00.523 --> 08:03.265
Our last medical director
raised...

08:03.308 --> 08:07.878
$3.4 million
on his first fund-raiser.

08:07.922 --> 08:09.619
- Big shoes.

08:09.663 --> 08:11.491
- And we fired him.

08:11.534 --> 08:13.710
[upbeat jazz music]

08:13.754 --> 08:15.059
- Hey.

08:15.103 --> 08:17.061
Did you, uh, get
that blood work I sent over

08:17.105 --> 08:18.802
for Manny Harris
in the Corrections Ward?

08:18.846 --> 08:20.543
- Oh, I saw it, all right.

08:20.587 --> 08:22.632
- Well, I was hoping to get
your professional opinion.

08:22.676 --> 08:24.721
- My professional opinion?
- Yeah.

08:24.765 --> 08:25.983
- Well, my professional opinion

08:26.027 --> 08:27.898
is that anybody
in this hospital

08:27.942 --> 08:30.161
could have read those labs,
and you only sent it to me

08:30.205 --> 08:32.903
in a pathetic
and poorly veiled attempt

08:32.947 --> 08:35.906
to make amends for insulting
my abilities as a doctor.

08:37.821 --> 08:38.996
- You're right.

08:39.040 --> 08:40.955
- I know I'm right.
- [sighs]

08:40.998 --> 08:42.826
- Just didn't think
that you knew I was right.

08:42.870 --> 08:44.567
- All right, look,
I'm sorry, all right?

08:44.611 --> 08:46.003
I am.

08:46.047 --> 08:48.005
You're an exceptional doctor,
all right?

08:48.049 --> 08:49.572
One of the best
I've ever worked with.

08:49.616 --> 08:52.053
In fact, I'll never question
your judgment again.

08:54.011 --> 08:55.665
Look, I owe you
a bottle of scotch

08:55.709 --> 08:59.843
just for putting up
with me, okay?

08:59.887 --> 09:02.759
All right, now this is where
you forgive me.

09:05.066 --> 09:06.850
- Fine, whatever.

09:06.894 --> 09:09.070
As for your prisoner's labs,
the only thing of note

09:09.113 --> 09:11.594
was that he tested positive
for Special K.

09:11.638 --> 09:13.161
- Ketamine.
Wow.

09:13.204 --> 09:15.119
He OD'd, huh?
- Yep.

09:15.163 --> 09:17.208
But when I admitted him
a week ago,

09:17.252 --> 09:19.254
he was clean
as a whistle, so...

09:19.297 --> 09:20.821
- He got the K in here.

09:20.864 --> 09:22.605
- Looks like someone's
smuggling drugs

09:22.649 --> 09:25.086
into our Corrections Ward.

09:27.349 --> 09:29.264
Hey, you and the kids
got this?

09:29.307 --> 09:31.658
I need to get all dolled up.
- Yeah, yeah.

09:31.701 --> 09:33.703
Get out of here.
- Drive safe, boys.

09:33.747 --> 09:35.749
- Hey, genius, what do you got
planned for us next year?

09:35.792 --> 09:37.707
What, are we gonna get
our appendix removed?

09:37.751 --> 09:39.317
- I don't think we should go
on these trips anymore, Dad.

09:39.361 --> 09:40.754
Clearly you're getting too old.

09:40.797 --> 09:42.712
- Says the man
in the wheelchair.

09:42.756 --> 09:44.714
- [gasps]
- Chris? Chris?

09:44.758 --> 09:46.237
What--what's wrong?
- [gasping]

09:46.281 --> 09:47.804
- Bloom, get back here!

09:47.848 --> 09:49.893
- What happened?
- He just started seizing.

09:49.937 --> 09:51.852
- Move that wheelchair!
I need Ativan, now!

09:51.895 --> 09:54.028
- [grunting]

09:54.071 --> 09:56.900
[dramatic music]

09:56.944 --> 09:58.336
- I got his head.
- I got him!

09:58.380 --> 10:00.077
- Bloom.
- What?

10:00.121 --> 10:02.297
- Grab his legs.
- [choking]

10:02.340 --> 10:05.039
♪

10:09.478 --> 10:09.609
.

10:09.652 --> 10:12.612
[indistinct chatter]

10:15.179 --> 10:16.790
- So...

10:16.833 --> 10:18.139
Hey.
- Hey.

10:18.182 --> 10:19.488
- You ready to raise
some money?

10:19.531 --> 10:21.403
- Absolutely.
You know, I was, uh,

10:21.446 --> 10:23.579
just about to chat up, uh,
this man.

10:23.623 --> 10:25.581
Looks like he has
about 14 yachts.

10:25.625 --> 10:28.845
- That's the caterer.

10:28.889 --> 10:31.631
- I meant, uh, the guy
next to him.

10:31.674 --> 10:33.807
- Andrew Nomura.
- Yeah.

10:33.850 --> 10:35.373
- Hedge fund.
- Mm-hmm.

10:35.417 --> 10:37.462
- $1.2 billion.
- Ooh, is that all?

10:37.506 --> 10:40.161
- Max, when you go up--
- I got this.

10:40.204 --> 10:41.771
I do.

10:41.815 --> 10:45.470
[breathes deeply,
clears throat]

10:45.514 --> 10:46.689
Hi.

10:46.733 --> 10:48.386
- You must be
the new medical director.

10:48.430 --> 10:50.519
- It's nice to meet you.
Thank you for coming.

10:50.562 --> 10:54.218
Um, I need to tell you
about a patient.

10:54.262 --> 10:55.829
Um...

11:03.184 --> 11:05.403
But, uh, sorry.

11:05.447 --> 11:07.405
I need to--excuse me.

11:13.237 --> 11:15.892
- I thought I'd surprise you.

11:17.720 --> 11:19.766
- You look amazing.

11:19.809 --> 11:21.202
- I'm celebrating.
- Hmm.

11:21.245 --> 11:23.291
- With you.

11:24.727 --> 11:26.511
[chuckles]

11:26.555 --> 11:28.731
- Just like old times.
- Mm-hmm.

11:28.775 --> 11:31.516
Except tonight we won't be
having sex in the coat room.

11:31.560 --> 11:33.736
- Says you.

11:33.780 --> 11:35.782
- What are the odds
of both men seizing

11:35.825 --> 11:37.697
within minutes of each other?
- Quite low.

11:37.740 --> 11:39.437
- I bet a seizure is why
the dad lost control

11:39.481 --> 11:40.830
of the car.
- CTs?

11:40.874 --> 11:42.658
- Well, they look normal,
but the CSF

11:42.702 --> 11:44.791
and the lumbar puncture showed
white and red cells for both.

11:44.834 --> 11:46.749
I thought a hematologist
should take a closer look.

11:46.793 --> 11:49.273
- It could be infection.
- Or exposure.

11:49.317 --> 11:50.710
- Which is why
I paged you both.

11:50.753 --> 11:52.537
And I believe in my heart
of hearts that you guys

11:52.581 --> 11:54.757
are gonna figure it out.
- "You guys"?

11:54.801 --> 11:56.759
- I am late
for a fund-raiser, Doctor.

11:56.803 --> 11:58.456
- Oh, that.

12:01.416 --> 12:03.331
- Guess who apologized.

12:03.374 --> 12:04.767
- No.

12:04.811 --> 12:07.552
- It was a sincere one, too--
really gushy.

12:07.596 --> 12:08.858
- How'd you feel about that?

12:08.902 --> 12:10.642
- I don't know.

12:10.686 --> 12:12.427
I mean, it was definitely
easier getting over him

12:12.470 --> 12:14.603
when he was being a dick.
- [chuckles]

12:14.646 --> 12:17.258
- Hey, you gonna come tonight?
- Um, I don't know.

12:17.301 --> 12:18.999
We'll see.
- Come.

12:19.042 --> 12:20.870
Well, you deserve
to have some fun.

12:20.914 --> 12:22.437
- [scoffs]

12:22.480 --> 12:24.395
- Because of your unusual
symptoms,

12:24.439 --> 12:26.746
it would be helpful to know
exactly where have you been

12:26.789 --> 12:28.965
and whom you have come
in contact with.

12:29.009 --> 12:31.228
- Well, like I said,
we've been outside the country.

12:31.272 --> 12:32.664
- Begged to go to Hawaii,

12:32.708 --> 12:34.797
but my son insisted
on northern Canada.

12:34.841 --> 12:36.494
- We take
a father-son adventure

12:36.538 --> 12:37.626
every year since my mom died.

12:37.669 --> 12:38.888
Every year he complains.

12:38.932 --> 12:40.237
- Have you ever tried
moose jerky?

12:40.281 --> 12:41.761
- I wanted to see the glaciers.

12:41.804 --> 12:43.763
- Yeah, what's left of them--
the snow was so wet,

12:43.806 --> 12:45.808
it was like trudging through
a Slurpee.

12:45.852 --> 12:47.854
- They don't appear
to understand the severity

12:47.897 --> 12:49.246
of their current situation.

12:49.290 --> 12:50.813
- Good, let's keep it that way.

12:50.857 --> 12:52.684
- I believe this is
Naegleriasis.

12:52.728 --> 12:55.252
- Mm, but there was no warm
water for swimming up there.

12:55.296 --> 12:56.993
An arbovirus is more likely

12:57.037 --> 12:58.647
if there were
mosquitoes around.

12:58.690 --> 13:00.780
- Perhaps we should test them
for rabies.

13:00.823 --> 13:02.825
If they slept in a room
with a bat...

13:02.869 --> 13:04.784
- If they'd slept in a room
with a bat,

13:04.827 --> 13:06.916
I'm confident
we'd have heard about it.

13:06.960 --> 13:09.701
- So we do a full panel?
- Yeah.

13:10.877 --> 13:14.010
[monitor beeping]
- Hey, wake up.

13:14.054 --> 13:16.796
You could have died today,
Manny.

13:16.839 --> 13:18.580
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

13:18.623 --> 13:20.321
I know it's rough in here,

13:20.364 --> 13:23.890
but you using like this,
it could kill you.

13:23.933 --> 13:26.544
- What are you talking about?

13:26.588 --> 13:28.808
- Come on.
The Special K you're using.

13:28.851 --> 13:30.853
- "Special K"?

13:30.897 --> 13:33.682
No, man.
I don't do that stuff.

13:33.725 --> 13:36.293
- Well, your blood work
says otherwise, my friend.

13:36.337 --> 13:38.513
- I said I don't do that.

13:38.556 --> 13:42.734
I'm just trying to do my bid
and get my ass up out of here.

13:42.778 --> 13:44.954
- Explain this.

13:44.998 --> 13:47.043
Come on, man, that's a new
injection site...

13:47.087 --> 13:49.916
from shooting up.

13:49.959 --> 13:52.875
- I ain't do nothing wrong.

13:52.919 --> 13:54.529
I ain't even start it.

13:54.572 --> 13:56.661
- What do you mean?
Start what?

13:56.705 --> 13:58.663
- The fight.

13:58.707 --> 14:00.709
Guy came at me.

14:00.752 --> 14:02.319
[beeping continues]

14:02.363 --> 14:05.453
Things popped off...

14:05.496 --> 14:07.759
then she stepped in.

14:12.460 --> 14:15.376
- She did this to you?

14:15.419 --> 14:17.595
- Yeah, so?

14:21.512 --> 14:23.384
- She can't do that.

14:26.648 --> 14:28.345
Why didn't you say anything?

14:28.389 --> 14:30.782
- To who?

14:30.826 --> 14:33.046
Who cares
about what happens to us?

14:38.703 --> 14:42.055
- Mom, I'm not gonna sit here
and pretend that this is okay.

14:44.013 --> 14:46.798
Well, I'm sorry
you feel that way.

14:46.842 --> 14:48.713
Mm-hmm.

14:48.757 --> 14:50.759
Yeah, bye.

14:52.413 --> 14:54.023
[sighs]
- Boo!

14:54.067 --> 14:55.677
- Oh, my gosh! Hi.

14:55.720 --> 14:57.113
Hi, my little meerkat.

14:57.157 --> 14:59.594
How you doing? Hi.

14:59.637 --> 15:01.552
- She remembered every hallway,
every turn.

15:01.596 --> 15:03.641
I couldn't keep up.
- Wow, amazing.

15:03.685 --> 15:05.643
You look nice.
- Mm, you look nice yourself.

15:05.687 --> 15:07.036
- Thank you.

15:07.080 --> 15:09.169
So is everybody sad
they have to stay at home

15:09.212 --> 15:10.910
with Jessie?
- They're watching a movie.

15:10.953 --> 15:12.955
- They're missing out.
- Come on, let's go.

15:12.999 --> 15:15.044
What if Grandpa and Grandma
are already there?

15:15.088 --> 15:16.654
- Been talking about them
the whole way here.

15:16.698 --> 15:19.005
- Yeah, about that, um...
- About what?

15:19.048 --> 15:20.920
- Hey, relax.

15:20.963 --> 15:23.748
Tonight's gonna be great.
You'll see.

15:23.792 --> 15:25.968
- Yeah, okay.

15:26.012 --> 15:27.578
- I have made myself
perfectly clear.

15:27.622 --> 15:28.884
The tickets were for her.

15:28.928 --> 15:30.755
- I honestly don't see
how you could have

15:30.799 --> 15:32.757
accidentally asked
this poor girl out on a date.

15:32.801 --> 15:34.585
- But she accepted.
- Of course she did.

15:34.629 --> 15:36.805
She was trapped
behind a croissant counter.

15:36.848 --> 15:38.067
- So what do I do?

15:38.111 --> 15:39.547
- "Do"?

15:39.590 --> 15:41.418
You can't do anything.
It's a disaster.

15:41.462 --> 15:44.813
Avoid her until you die.
- Dr. Kapoor, Dr. Sharpe.

15:44.856 --> 15:46.771
The Markens have been moved
into isolation,

15:46.815 --> 15:48.599
and here are
their test results.

15:48.643 --> 15:50.775
- Could you get us hard copies?
- Printers are down.

15:50.819 --> 15:53.604
- Get IT on those printers and
find us another tablet, please.

15:53.648 --> 15:55.476
[dramatic music]

15:55.519 --> 15:58.087
- It's not Naegleriasis
or botulism.

15:58.131 --> 16:00.046
♪

16:00.089 --> 16:02.222
- It's not anything.

16:02.265 --> 16:04.876
All their tests are clean.

16:04.920 --> 16:07.096
But something's wrong
with them.

16:07.140 --> 16:09.925
- There's one possibility
we have not yet considered.

16:09.969 --> 16:11.796
♪

16:11.840 --> 16:14.712
[cheers and applause]

16:14.756 --> 16:16.018
- Good evening.

16:16.062 --> 16:18.629
Uh, I'm Dr. Max Goodwin,

16:18.673 --> 16:21.241
Medical Director
of New Amsterdam,

16:21.284 --> 16:23.069
and I need to fill this, uh,

16:23.112 --> 16:25.462
weird thermometer thing
behind me

16:25.506 --> 16:27.943
with, uh, your money.
[laughter]

16:27.987 --> 16:32.208
Um, I need to tell you
about a patient...

16:32.252 --> 16:36.082
and--and why she matters to us

16:36.125 --> 16:39.911
and why she should matter
to, um...

16:39.955 --> 16:42.262
um...

16:42.305 --> 16:44.525
to you.

16:44.568 --> 16:47.528
[stammering]
You can look forward to that

16:47.571 --> 16:48.920
and--and much, much more.

16:48.964 --> 16:50.661
uh, just a few minutes,

16:50.705 --> 16:53.621
Just, um, please enjoy
the free champagne.

16:53.664 --> 16:57.016
[audience murmuring]

17:03.065 --> 17:04.980
I'm not busy or anything.

17:05.024 --> 17:06.503
- We have two patients
in isolation

17:06.547 --> 17:08.070
who are exhibiting
identical symptoms.

17:08.114 --> 17:10.507
They recently returned from
hiking the Canadian Rockies.

17:10.551 --> 17:12.161
- On melting permafrost.

17:12.205 --> 17:13.945
- We have tested them
for every known disease,

17:13.989 --> 17:15.556
but nothing has come back
positive.

17:15.599 --> 17:17.775
What's more, their condition
is only getting worse.

17:17.819 --> 17:19.995
- Their BPs are falling,
and their fevers are spiking.

17:20.039 --> 17:21.518
- As more and more ice thaws,

17:21.562 --> 17:24.173
long-dormant pathogens
are waking up.

17:24.217 --> 17:27.176
- Are you telling me there may
be some ancient disease

17:27.220 --> 17:28.873
floating around our hospital?

17:28.917 --> 17:30.919
- Yes, we are.
- Yeah, that's about right.

17:35.880 --> 17:36.055
.

17:36.098 --> 17:38.927
- Look, I'm not saying
it isn't some ancient pathogen

17:38.970 --> 17:40.189
that we've never heard of,
can't test for,

17:40.233 --> 17:41.756
and couldn't possibly treat.

17:41.799 --> 17:44.193
I am simply suggesting
that we should focus

17:44.237 --> 17:47.501
on other diseases that we could
actually, you know, cure.

17:47.544 --> 17:50.373
- We've been through it, Max.
- Vasculitis?

17:50.417 --> 17:52.897
- Their kidney function's fine.
- Carbon monoxide.

17:52.941 --> 17:55.248
- Wouldn't account
for the seizures.

17:55.291 --> 17:57.119
- Marantic endocarditis.

17:57.163 --> 17:59.774
- We'd have seen thrombotic
vegetations in the CTs.

17:59.817 --> 18:01.080
- [sighs]

18:01.123 --> 18:03.038
[dramatic music]

18:03.082 --> 18:05.084
[no audible dialogue]

18:05.127 --> 18:08.043
Mercury poisoning?

18:08.087 --> 18:10.263
I read the Arctic permafrost
has something like

18:10.306 --> 18:13.396
20 swimming pools
of pure mercury.

18:13.440 --> 18:15.355
- The more the ice melts,
the more mercury

18:15.398 --> 18:16.921
is released
into the ecosystem.

18:16.965 --> 18:19.315
Our patients hike through,
absorb it...

18:19.359 --> 18:21.143
- It would indeed fit
the symptoms.

18:21.187 --> 18:23.102
- We'll work up a treatment
of dimercaprol right away.

18:23.145 --> 18:25.930
- Great, and while you two are
here heroically saving lives,

18:25.974 --> 18:29.412
I will be charming rich people
out of their money.

18:30.500 --> 18:34.504
- ♪ I was left there
in the dark ♪

18:34.548 --> 18:37.942
♪ Blinded
by your glowing light ♪

18:37.986 --> 18:39.988
- That is quite the dress.

18:40.031 --> 18:41.424
- Oh, thank you.

18:41.468 --> 18:43.513
Uh, it is my response
to wearing formal scrubs

18:43.557 --> 18:45.254
for eight weeks straight.
- [laughs]

18:45.298 --> 18:47.996
- How are you, Evie?
- Hi.

18:48.039 --> 18:49.998
Oh, crap.
I owe you a call, don't I?

18:50.041 --> 18:52.261
- Oh, we were supposed
to grab lunch six months ago.

18:52.305 --> 18:53.915
- I'm so sorry.

18:53.958 --> 18:55.569
Well, how are things upstairs?
- It's good.

18:55.612 --> 18:57.223
Just trying to keep
you troublemakers

18:57.266 --> 18:59.138
out of trouble
with my bright legal mind.

18:59.181 --> 19:00.965
- Yeah, and how's Robert?
- Ugh.

19:01.009 --> 19:02.793
That man couldn't handle
anything real.

19:02.837 --> 19:04.317
- Mm.
- He couldn't handle a strong,

19:04.360 --> 19:07.320
intelligent woman,
so he's black history.

19:07.363 --> 19:09.278
[both laughing]

19:09.322 --> 19:11.976
I'm so happy I ran into you.
The legal department is--

19:12.020 --> 19:13.456
- Okay, I'm gonna
stop you there. Count me in.

19:13.500 --> 19:15.458
But I need to cram at least
two drinks into my system

19:15.502 --> 19:17.286
so I can't get called into
work, and you're gonna join me.

19:17.330 --> 19:18.853
- Absolutely.

19:18.896 --> 19:20.376
- And he wanted you to know
that he's sorry.

19:20.420 --> 19:22.248
He's just...

19:22.291 --> 19:24.989
curing an ancient disease.

19:25.033 --> 19:27.862
And, yes, I do know
how that sounds.

19:27.905 --> 19:30.169
[band vocalizing]

19:30.212 --> 19:33.084
♪

19:33.128 --> 19:35.086
♪ Bring the beat in

19:35.130 --> 19:39.003
- Excuse me. Were you with
The Elizabeth Mills Company?

19:39.047 --> 19:41.919
- That's right, I was.
I am.

19:41.963 --> 19:43.312
- I saw you perform at BAM.

19:43.356 --> 19:45.314
That was extraordinary,
and you were wonderful.

19:45.358 --> 19:46.533
- Thank you.

19:46.576 --> 19:49.188
I, uh--I can't wait
to get back.

19:49.231 --> 19:51.451
- Forgive me, I was just gonna
borrow this young lady

19:51.494 --> 19:53.583
for a quick boogie.

19:53.627 --> 19:57.587
- ♪ I'm knowing no pain

19:57.631 --> 19:59.198
- Max.
- Mm-hmm.

19:59.241 --> 20:01.461
- Do you know who that was?
- Andrew Nomura?

20:01.504 --> 20:04.028
Worth only $1.2 billion?

20:04.072 --> 20:06.596
- Mm-hmm.

20:06.640 --> 20:09.338
If you want this night
to be a success,

20:09.382 --> 20:11.340
you should really be dancing
with him right now.

20:11.384 --> 20:13.037
- Mm.
[clicks tongue]

20:13.081 --> 20:15.039
You know what? I'll ask him
to do the Funky Chicken

20:15.083 --> 20:17.259
right after I'm through
with you.

20:17.303 --> 20:18.521
- Can I cut in?

20:18.565 --> 20:21.611
- ♪ Fight through my tears

20:21.655 --> 20:23.526
- This had better be good.

20:23.570 --> 20:26.355
- So you're saying my guards
are tranquilizing prisoners?

20:26.399 --> 20:28.270
- Not all of them, Gloria.

20:28.314 --> 20:29.924
Just the newest recruit.
- Codie Jeffers.

20:29.967 --> 20:31.534
I believe she used ketamine
to sedate a guy

20:31.578 --> 20:33.232
she felt was acting up.

20:33.275 --> 20:36.017
Now, in an untrained hand,
that's potentially lethal.

20:36.060 --> 20:37.540
- That's a serious
accusation, Max.

20:37.584 --> 20:39.325
- We wouldn't be bringing it
to you otherwise, Warden.

20:39.368 --> 20:41.327
- Our floor isn't a cake-walk
but all of my guards

20:41.370 --> 20:43.067
are thoroughly vetted.

20:43.111 --> 20:45.200
- I'm sure, but that doesn't
mean that a bad apple

20:45.244 --> 20:47.115
won't slip through
from time to time.

20:47.158 --> 20:50.510
- You can't expect me to go
on the hearsay of one prisoner.

20:50.553 --> 20:52.251
Is there proof?

20:52.294 --> 20:55.036
- Look, no, but this patient
was telling the truth.

20:55.079 --> 20:56.907
- I'm sorry,
but Rikers is filled

20:56.951 --> 20:58.300
with incredibly good liars.

20:58.344 --> 21:00.084
- Look, he's not lying.
- Okay, okay.

21:00.128 --> 21:02.130
The only way that we're gonna
solve this problem

21:02.173 --> 21:04.524
is if we work together,
because the hospital and Rikers

21:04.567 --> 21:06.569
are in
a symbiotic relationship.

21:06.613 --> 21:09.485
So we just want to support you
in correcting this.

21:09.529 --> 21:11.139
- "Support me"?

21:11.182 --> 21:13.228
I'll run my prison.
You run your hospital.

21:15.099 --> 21:17.014
- Thank you, Warden.

21:20.975 --> 21:23.543
- I don't understand--you think
we have mercury poisoning?

21:23.586 --> 21:26.328
- Confirmatory tests
would take weeks...

21:26.372 --> 21:28.243
weeks you don't have.

21:28.287 --> 21:31.115
We're acting now to give you
the best chance for survival.

21:31.159 --> 21:34.945
- We want to treat you
with an agent called BAL.

21:34.989 --> 21:38.427
It binds to the mercury
and strips it out of your body.

21:38.471 --> 21:41.474
- What if we don't have
mercury poisoning?

21:41.517 --> 21:44.041
- Then it bonds to the proteins
in your blood

21:44.085 --> 21:46.740
and strips them instead...

21:46.783 --> 21:51.614
which is why we'd like to start
by treating only one of you...

21:51.658 --> 21:54.051
to see how you respond.

21:54.095 --> 21:57.054
[dramatic music]

21:57.098 --> 21:58.708
- I'll go.

21:58.752 --> 22:00.188
♪

22:00.231 --> 22:01.450
I'll go.

22:01.494 --> 22:03.583
You do me.
- Dad, wait--

22:03.626 --> 22:04.758
- No.

22:04.801 --> 22:08.152
I'm older. I'm your father.

22:08.196 --> 22:10.241
And if something were
to go wrong...

22:10.285 --> 22:12.200
- Unfortunately,
we're gonna need

22:12.243 --> 22:13.767
to start with Christopher.

22:13.810 --> 22:16.335
He's younger.

22:16.378 --> 22:19.468
His system can better handle
the harsh side effects.

22:19.512 --> 22:24.691
♪

22:24.734 --> 22:28.085
- It's okay, Dad.

22:28.129 --> 22:30.261
I got this.

22:30.305 --> 22:34.135
♪

22:34.178 --> 22:37.443
- ♪ No one can tell you

22:37.486 --> 22:40.359
- Are they stuck in traffic
or what?

22:40.402 --> 22:44.101
- Yeah,
that's probably it, hon.

22:44.145 --> 22:46.147
That one looks really good,
by the way.

22:46.190 --> 22:49.106
- Nuh-uh.
It has to be perfect.

22:49.150 --> 22:52.501
Can I get some more napkins?
- Sure, honey.

22:52.545 --> 22:54.416
- Careful.

22:54.460 --> 22:57.680
- ♪ Take off your armor

22:57.724 --> 23:00.291
- Iggy, what's going on?

23:00.335 --> 23:03.643
- They bailed.
- [sighs] No.

23:03.686 --> 23:05.296
- Yeah.

23:05.340 --> 23:09.431
Yeah, last-minute plans
with old friends.

23:09.475 --> 23:11.694
Decided it would be best
not to give us the wrong idea.

23:11.738 --> 23:14.654
Direct quote.
- Unbelievable.

23:14.697 --> 23:17.221
♪

23:17.265 --> 23:19.659
Why didn't you just tell her?

23:19.702 --> 23:22.313
- When?

23:22.357 --> 23:23.706
How?

23:23.750 --> 23:26.709
I don't even know
what to say.

23:26.753 --> 23:29.408
- The truth would be
a good start.

23:29.451 --> 23:30.583
♪

23:30.626 --> 23:32.628
- "The truth"?

23:32.672 --> 23:34.674
That two gay dads
and their Muslim kids

23:34.717 --> 23:36.415
aren't worthy of love?

23:36.458 --> 23:38.460
♪

23:38.504 --> 23:41.420
She's already had one family
taken away from her.

23:41.463 --> 23:47.208
♪

23:47.251 --> 23:50.211
[suspenseful music]

23:50.254 --> 23:52.213
♪

23:52.256 --> 23:54.084
- [gasps]
[monitor blaring]

23:54.128 --> 23:56.391
- Hey, Christopher!
- [choking]

23:56.435 --> 23:58.349
- What's happened to my boy?
- [choking]

23:58.393 --> 24:00.351
[blaring continues]

24:00.395 --> 24:03.442
- BP's bottoming out.
- Heart rate's climbing.

24:03.485 --> 24:05.618
Blood in the urine.
- His kidneys are failing.

24:05.661 --> 24:06.793
- What's happening to my boy?

24:06.836 --> 24:08.359
- BAL is tearing through
his body.

24:08.403 --> 24:12.451
Pass me the Ambu bag.
- [choking]

24:12.494 --> 24:15.410
- It should have been me.

24:15.454 --> 24:16.846
- [choking]
- It's not mercury.

24:16.890 --> 24:19.327
- It should have been me!
I told you!

24:19.370 --> 24:21.460
You should have tested it
on me!

24:28.075 --> 24:28.292
.

24:28.336 --> 24:31.339
- Is he gonna be all right?

24:31.382 --> 24:35.038
- We are in uncharted waters
here, Mr. Merken.

24:35.082 --> 24:39.913
- But--but you have to be able
to do something, right?

24:39.956 --> 24:42.481
- Your son's reaction
to the BAL has provided us

24:42.524 --> 24:44.483
with invaluable information.

24:44.526 --> 24:47.834
- Information we will use
to seek out...

24:47.877 --> 24:50.489
Another diagnosis.

24:50.532 --> 24:54.275
- So you really have no idea
what we have or how to cure it.

24:54.318 --> 24:56.364
[monitor beeping,
respirator whirring]

24:56.407 --> 24:57.757
- No.

24:57.800 --> 24:59.846
- [sighs]

24:59.889 --> 25:03.502
[breathing shakily]

25:03.545 --> 25:06.461
Every year, um, we...

25:08.245 --> 25:11.379
Take these adventures together,
and, uh...

25:11.422 --> 25:13.381
[somber music]

25:13.424 --> 25:17.080
And I complain, and...

25:17.124 --> 25:20.214
Chris complains
that I complain.

25:20.257 --> 25:23.304
♪

25:23.347 --> 25:25.219
But the truth is, is that...

25:25.262 --> 25:28.439
♪

25:28.483 --> 25:30.093
I look forward to these trips

25:30.137 --> 25:32.792
more than anything
in the world.

25:32.835 --> 25:39.276
♪

25:39.320 --> 25:41.452
Now that he's grown, I...

25:41.496 --> 25:43.890
that's all...

25:43.933 --> 25:46.545
that's the only time
that I have with him.

25:46.588 --> 25:52.115
♪

25:52.159 --> 25:54.901
We don't get enough time.

25:54.944 --> 26:01.081
♪

26:01.124 --> 26:04.171
We just don't get enough time
with our kids.

26:04.214 --> 26:08.915
♪

26:08.958 --> 26:10.481
- How do you want
to handle this?

26:10.525 --> 26:12.266
- Well, if she gets away with
it once, she'll do it again.

26:12.309 --> 26:14.094
We can't just wait around
until somebody dies.

26:14.137 --> 26:15.748
- But the Corrections Ward
is Salazar's domain.

26:15.791 --> 26:17.010
- Yeah, and we're the ones

26:17.053 --> 26:18.881
that have to take care
of the patients.

26:18.925 --> 26:20.274
- Right, so if you piss off the
guards, what's gonna happen?

26:20.317 --> 26:22.058
- We lose our protection.

26:22.102 --> 26:23.451
- I don't know about you,
but I doubt our staff's

26:23.494 --> 26:25.018
gonna want to go in there
without them,

26:25.061 --> 26:26.541
which means
the patients would suffer,

26:26.585 --> 26:28.282
So, if we're gonna do this
we're gonna do it right.

26:28.325 --> 26:29.457
[pager beeps]
What?

26:29.500 --> 26:30.806
- Another code.
Corrections Ward.

26:30.850 --> 26:32.112
I got to do something, Max.

26:32.155 --> 26:33.940
- ♪ Let me take you there...

26:33.983 --> 26:36.290
- This new director's
so radical, he's not even here.

26:36.333 --> 26:37.944
If he wants us to pony up,

26:37.987 --> 26:40.120
he should at least make
an appearance.

26:40.163 --> 26:42.165
- You're not giving this year?

26:42.209 --> 26:44.603
- Where are the touching
patient stories?

26:44.646 --> 26:46.561
Where are the flashy speeches

26:46.605 --> 26:48.171
about cutting-edge
achievements?

26:48.215 --> 26:50.130
'Cause I didn't come
for the food.

26:50.173 --> 26:52.872
- Don't knock it
till you try it.

26:52.915 --> 26:55.048
I'm sorry, I, um--

26:55.091 --> 26:58.051
I've been on bed rest,
so, to me, this is--

26:58.094 --> 27:00.140
it's like New Year's
in Paris.

27:00.183 --> 27:01.968
♪

27:02.011 --> 27:03.317
There are a few things
you should know

27:03.360 --> 27:05.493
